				\begin{document}$${C}_{{\rm{max }}}$$\end{document}. The lubricity of the fluid affects how fast the disc can spin, thereby setting the rate of capacitance variation. The lubricant must be nonvolatile (i.e., have a low vapor pressure at the working temperature) to keep the integrity of the device. The lubricant can either be an ionic liquid (IL) or a low volatility molecular liquid. Lubricants such as perfluoropolyether, which are used in extreme lubrication applications, have a too low dielectric constant, and therefore cannot be readily employed in the device presented in this work. Instead, ILs feature large capacitance even when the gap distance, l\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
